President Cyril Ramaphosa has declared that there will be a special official funeral for King Goodwill Zwelithini. The AmaZulu King passed away in hospital after a long illness early on Friday. He's been hailed by many as a champion for peace and regarded as a dedicated leader. eNCA's Lethiwe Mdluli tells us more. JOHANNESBURG - Kwazulu Natal Premier, Sihle Zikalala, announced that the province would observe a week of mourning for the late AmaZulu King, Goodwill Zwelithini. The Zulu monach passed away Friday morning at the Inkosi Albert Luthuli Central Hospital in Durban, after battling with diabetes. He served as the monarch for almost 50-years. READ: EXCLUSIVE: Prince Buthelezi speaks on passing of AmaZulu King A prayer session will also be held on 18 March. The provincial government will visit the royal house on Saturday to discuss funeral arrangements. Zikalala has described Zwelithini as a pillar of the nation as well as a champion for peace. "In his legacy we must allude how he contributed in ensuring that there is a promotion of traditional institutions within the democratic system," he says. The Royal Family has confirmed the mortal remains of the King will lie in state at Khethomthandayo Royal Palace. President Cyril Ramaphosa has paid tribute to the King. SA is mourning the death of the Amazulu King, Goodwill Zwelithini. The 72-year-old passed away on Friday at the Inkosi Albert Luthuli Central Hospital in Durban. eNCA's Lethiwe Mdluli is following this story. #DStv403 pic.twitter.com/7KNCWGZJFI